WEBVTT

00:00:00.480 --> 00:00:06.400
Okay, great. Hi, my name is Demetri. You may know me from formerly bird-themed social media websites.

00:00:07.440 --> 00:00:10.480
But if you don't know me, that's okay. We can start with a little bit about me.

00:00:11.040 --> 00:00:17.920
I'm 11,207 souls old and I traveled 2 times 10 to the minus 5 astronomical units to get here.

00:00:20.799 --> 00:00:26.000
It's probably not very helpful, eh? Maybe more helpful if I tell you I'm 32 years old.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.959
I traveled 3,200 kilometers to get here, or since we're in the States, 2,000 miles.

00:00:33.439 --> 00:00:37.200
What was the point of all this? Why am I telling you this? Well, the point I'm trying to make here

00:00:37.919 --> 00:00:44.080
is that the way in which we talk about comparisons is really important for understanding those

00:00:44.080 --> 00:00:49.040
comparisons. Now, I get it. Years is a unit of time. It's not a comparison. But when I tell you

00:00:49.040 --> 00:00:54.560
my age in years, you can make a comparison. My age against yours, my age against the year.

00:00:55.439 --> 00:00:59.759
When I tell you my age in souls, which is the length of a Martian day,

00:01:00.880 --> 00:01:06.000
those comparisons become a lot harder to understand. The same is true of the astronomical

00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:10.239
unit. When I say 2 times 10 to the minus 5, that sounds like a short distance.

00:01:10.959 --> 00:01:15.040
Unless you know that the astronomical unit is the distance from Earth to the sun.

00:01:16.320 --> 00:01:20.320
Okay, so the way in which we talk about comparisons really matters. Why does it matter?

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:24.879
Well, it matters because good comparisons are crucial for telling compelling stories.

00:01:24.879 --> 00:01:30.879
And we, as data scientists, do nothing if not make comparisons and tell compelling stories,

00:01:30.879 --> 00:01:35.760
right? In fact, some of the tools that we use in pursuit of that goal, like regression,

00:01:35.760 --> 00:01:42.800
are just mini machines for creating comparisons. Now, of course, not every comparison which comes

00:01:42.800 --> 00:01:48.160
out the other side of a regression is immediately understandable. Take, for example, logistic

00:01:48.400 --> 00:01:54.000
regression, right? Logistic regression talks about comparisons in terms of odds ratios and odds.

00:01:54.879 --> 00:01:59.360
I'm going to argue to you for a moment that is a really bad way to talk about comparisons. So

00:01:59.360 --> 00:02:06.160
consider the following. I ran two polls on that bird website. The first poll gave some hypothetical

00:02:06.160 --> 00:02:10.639
information about data scientists and engineers and their attendance rate at this conference.

00:02:10.639 --> 00:02:15.679
I said, the probability an engineer attends PositConf is 10% and the probability a data

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:21.520
scientist attends twice as large. Notice I'm making a comparison here, data scientists and

00:02:21.520 --> 00:02:29.279
engineers, and I'm doing so using probability. Okay. Then I asked participants, what is the

00:02:29.279 --> 00:02:34.080
probability that a data scientist goes to PositConf? Give me the numerical value.

00:02:34.720 --> 00:02:38.800
And because the numbers are nice and I think the comparison is a good one, you can see that most

00:02:38.800 --> 00:02:45.679
people get the correct answer here, highlighted in green. Two times 10% is 20%. Okay. All right.

00:02:45.679 --> 00:02:53.119
I ran a second poll on that bird website. This time I changed the comparison to use odds. Everything

00:02:53.119 --> 00:02:57.520
else remained the same. I just said the odds a data scientist attends PositConf are twice as large.

00:02:58.240 --> 00:03:01.839
Again, I asked participants, what is the probability a data scientist goes to PositConf?

00:03:01.839 --> 00:03:09.039
Give me the numerical value. Now the answers look very different. All right. You can see that

00:03:09.039 --> 00:03:12.960
the correct answer here highlighted in green is not selected the majority of the time. And in fact,

00:03:12.960 --> 00:03:16.720
there's uncertainty as to what the answer should be. People are kind of spread out between three.

00:03:17.520 --> 00:03:22.000
So what's going on here? Well, I suspect that there are two kinds of people, right? There's

00:03:22.000 --> 00:03:27.039
the group of people who think that probability and odds are interchangeable. Sadly, they aren't.

00:03:27.839 --> 00:03:32.720
There's probably another group of people who know that odds and probability are not interchangeable,

00:03:32.720 --> 00:03:37.600
but lack the intuition for if the answer should be greater than 20% or less than 20%. And with

00:03:37.600 --> 00:03:42.960
that group of people, I can commiserate, right? Take a look at the formula for odds in terms of

00:03:42.960 --> 00:03:47.039
probability. It's like this nonlinear function to get the right answer. I got to like, okay,

00:03:47.039 --> 00:03:49.919
I'll take the probability. I got to convert it to odds. Then I got to do the comparison. I got

00:03:49.919 --> 00:03:56.639
back calculating the probability. It's filled with this mental friction, which is obfuscating

00:03:57.199 --> 00:04:03.440
the stories here. Now I know what you're thinking. You're thinking, Dimitri,

00:04:04.320 --> 00:04:09.919
this data is from Twitter. It's from a group of people who self-select into following you.

00:04:09.919 --> 00:04:13.919
This is not a good comparison in and of itself. And here you are on stage of PositKon,

00:04:13.919 --> 00:04:17.920
trying to tell me what constitutes a good comparison. And to that, I say, yes, correct.

00:04:19.519 --> 00:04:25.679
But, or rather, and, I think it highlights something else about comparisons. And that

00:04:25.679 --> 00:04:31.040
is language is not the only thing that matters. In a room full of data scientists, I really hope

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:36.160
that I don't have to belabor the point that bias is omnipresent, right? Quality of our

00:04:36.160 --> 00:04:45.279
comparisons depends on from whom and how that data was collected. So we as data scientists

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:51.119
have a really hard job. We need to communicate in an easily understood language, right? To talk

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:57.119
about age and years, not in souls. We need to create unbiased comparisons where possible. And

00:04:57.119 --> 00:05:03.359
we need to do all of this while telling a compelling story. Well, what do we use to do?

00:05:04.320 --> 00:05:09.200
And how do we do so? There's lots of tools that you can use. I'm going to add one more to your

00:05:09.200 --> 00:05:15.200
toolbox. It's called marginal effects. Marginal effects is a package that you can use to generate

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:20.640
counterfactual comparisons from over a hundred different kinds of models. Literally a hundred.

00:05:20.720 --> 00:05:24.959
I'm talking linear regression, logistic regression, generalized linear models, generalized

00:05:24.959 --> 00:05:30.160
additive models, Bayesian models, even some types of machine learning models are compatible with

00:05:30.160 --> 00:05:35.040
the marginal effects ecosystem. You can use marginal effects to reweight your comparisons

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:40.559
so that they better match a target population. And you can use marginal effect to cut down

00:05:40.559 --> 00:05:44.399
on the boiler plate that you would typically write in service of telling your story.

00:05:45.279 --> 00:05:50.239
The best part is, is that marginal effects is available for both R and

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:56.959
that's the what, what's the how? Well, I think by following these three steps,

00:05:56.959 --> 00:06:02.079
we can accomplish our goal. By writing your comparison as a function, by specifying the

00:06:02.079 --> 00:06:07.600
weights of groups in your population, and then using marginal effects to handle the plots and

00:06:07.600 --> 00:06:12.720
all the math, you can communicate to your audience in a way which is most natural to them, which

00:06:12.720 --> 00:06:20.000
results in you telling a more compelling story. And to illustrate these three steps, I want to

00:06:20.000 --> 00:06:28.720
tell you about a true-ish example. In a former life, I used to work in A-B testing, experimentation

00:06:28.720 --> 00:06:33.600
basically. And I would have colleagues come to me for help in the design and the analysis of

00:06:33.600 --> 00:06:37.760
the experiments they would run. And one day a colleague comes to me and says, Dimitri, I need

00:06:37.760 --> 00:06:43.200
some help. We ran this experiment. We wanted to improve the converted rate of this widget.

00:06:43.839 --> 00:06:49.359
And we changed the corners of our buy now button to have rounded corners instead of square corners.

00:06:50.079 --> 00:06:54.079
We think that the effect of the treatment is going to be different depending on if you're

00:06:54.079 --> 00:06:58.320
on desktop or mobile. So, you know, we've got this interaction with treatment here.

00:06:59.040 --> 00:07:04.720
And, you know, I'm pretty happy with this model, but my PM wants me to report something called

00:07:04.720 --> 00:07:10.720
the lift. I know that logistic regression outputs odds and odds ratios. So what do I do here? Do I

00:07:10.720 --> 00:07:15.359
need to fit a different model? Should I teach them how to understand odds? I went, whoa, whoa,

00:07:16.000 --> 00:07:20.160
let's not get too hasty. Let's not teach anybody how to understand odds. We know that's very

00:07:20.160 --> 00:07:25.040
difficult. And the best part is that we don't have to do either of these things. We can use

00:07:25.040 --> 00:07:30.239
marginal effects. And I walked through the following steps. I said, can you write down

00:07:30.239 --> 00:07:33.839
what the lift is? Like don't even worry about code right now. Just write it down pen and paper.

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:39.119
And they wrote down something that looks like this. You know, the lift is the difference in

00:07:40.239 --> 00:07:44.160
conversion rates between treatment and control divided by the conversion rate control.

00:07:44.880 --> 00:07:48.559
I said, cool, good start. Can you write that in terms of an R function now? And they wrote

00:07:48.559 --> 00:07:52.160
down something that looks like this. Again, we're going to take the mean outcome in treatment,

00:07:52.880 --> 00:07:56.959
subtract the mean outcome in control, and then divide by the mean outcome in control.

00:07:56.959 --> 00:08:02.399
So, I mean, that's all you need to get started using marginal effects. You can use the average

00:08:02.399 --> 00:08:08.160
comparisons function, which takes as its argument the model you fit, the comparison that you want

00:08:08.160 --> 00:08:13.040
to make, and the variable in your model for which you would like to compute that comparison. And you

00:08:13.040 --> 00:08:17.679
can see that marginal effects is now reporting a lift of seven and a half percent. That means

00:08:17.679 --> 00:08:21.600
treatment did better. And you get all the typical output that you would want from a statistical

00:08:21.600 --> 00:08:27.040
analysis, right? Standard errors, p-value, confidence interval. I told my colleague,

00:08:27.040 --> 00:08:31.359
now I know that your PM said that they wanted the lift, but they don't want one number. They

00:08:31.359 --> 00:08:37.280
want two numbers. They want the lift for each device type. To do that, you can use the buyer.

00:08:37.919 --> 00:08:41.280
Simply pass the name of the variable in your model for which you would like to compute this

00:08:41.280 --> 00:08:46.400
comparison within levels. So now we can see that desktop users have a lift of about 11 percent,

00:08:47.200 --> 00:08:52.960
confidence intervals, standard errors, etc. And mobile users have a lift of minus 58 percent. So

00:08:53.679 --> 00:08:59.840
this experiment was not very good for mobile users. So what I wanted my colleague to take

00:08:59.840 --> 00:09:04.320
away from this is that you just need to write your comparison as a function, and then you can

00:09:04.320 --> 00:09:09.679
use the average comparisons function to get that comparison as well as all the typical statistical

00:09:09.679 --> 00:09:14.799
output that you typically want. And you can use the buy argument to get comparisons within groups

00:09:14.799 --> 00:09:21.599
of a third variable. So my colleague was like, seven and a half percent? Great. I can take that

00:09:21.599 --> 00:09:27.280
back to my stakeholder. Thanks, Dimitri. Oh yeah, one more thing. There's always one more thing.

00:09:28.239 --> 00:09:32.400
And my colleague said, well, you know, we decided to add mobile users actually on the last day.

00:09:32.960 --> 00:09:37.679
This was originally supposed to be an experiment just for desktop users, but we weren't going to

00:09:37.679 --> 00:09:43.359
hit our sample size in time. So we added mobile users on the last day. Hey, is that OK? That's not

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:48.239
a big deal, right? I was like, actually, that's a very big deal. Right now, your experiment weights

00:09:48.239 --> 00:09:52.719
don't match your population weights. And I showed them a data frame that kind of looked like this.

00:09:52.880 --> 00:09:58.880
I said, in your population, 60% of users are on desktop. But in your experiment,

00:09:58.880 --> 00:10:04.719
94% were on desktop. Do you know what that means? They shook their head, no. And I said,

00:10:04.719 --> 00:10:10.080
that means that seven and a half percent that we just estimated is biased. And it's biased

00:10:10.080 --> 00:10:15.440
towards desktop users. Not to worry, though. We can use marginal effects to correct for this.

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:20.000
We just have to follow a few steps. The first thing we're going to do is we're going to take

00:10:20.000 --> 00:10:25.119
that comparison function. I'm going to rewrite it to be a weighted comparison function. You can

00:10:25.119 --> 00:10:30.640
see here that I'm adding a third variable, w, here for the weights. And everywhere that I used mean

00:10:30.640 --> 00:10:34.960
in my function body, I'm just now going to use weighted. See, I'm taking the weighted difference

00:10:34.960 --> 00:10:41.200
between treatment and control. And I'll divide by the weighted mean. Then we just change a few

00:10:41.200 --> 00:10:45.919
arguments in our average comparison scope. You can see now that I'm passing the weighted comparison

00:10:45.919 --> 00:10:52.640
to the comparison argument. I've passed that data frame that had the population weights to the new

00:10:52.640 --> 00:10:57.760
data argument. And I'm telling average comparisons which column in that data frame contains the

00:10:57.760 --> 00:11:04.320
weights that I want to use. And you can see that now marginal effects is reporting a different

00:11:04.320 --> 00:11:11.280
estimate of minus 13%. So that means that treatment did worse overall. And why is that?

00:11:11.280 --> 00:11:16.239
That's because the treatment did worse for mobile users. And there are more mobile users in our

00:11:16.239 --> 00:11:24.159
population than there were. So what I wanted my colleague to take away from this is that bias can

00:11:24.159 --> 00:11:28.640
result from improper weighting of groups. You can fix that with marginal effects. You can specify

00:11:28.640 --> 00:11:34.400
the weights of the groups in your population in a data frame. And then you can pass those

00:11:34.400 --> 00:11:40.719
weights to the average comparisons function to get your appropriate comparison. So my colleague was

00:11:40.719 --> 00:11:46.000
like, whoa, thanks, Dimitri, for catching that. Now I need to make some plots. This is such an

00:11:46.000 --> 00:11:50.080
important thing that I need to convey this to my stakeholder. And the best way to do that is

00:11:50.080 --> 00:11:55.919
probably visually, not math. I agreed. I said, but marginal effects can do that, too. So why don't

00:11:55.919 --> 00:12:01.760
you tell me what you want to show your stakeholder? Maybe we can partner on this. And my colleague

00:12:01.760 --> 00:12:06.080
said, well, I think I just want to show them the conversion rates first. And they hummed and hawed.

00:12:06.080 --> 00:12:10.880
And they described this ggplot that they wanted to make, where treatment was on the x-axis,

00:12:10.880 --> 00:12:18.239
conversion rate was on the y. I said, yeah, that's true. But remember here, the experiment data is

00:12:18.239 --> 00:12:22.719
biased. You need to weight it. And instead of munging and doing all these weighted means in

00:12:22.719 --> 00:12:27.280
dplyr, you can just use marginal effects. I'm going to use the plot predictions function here,

00:12:27.280 --> 00:12:32.239
which takes as its argument my model. To the by argument, I'm passing what I want on the x-axis

00:12:32.239 --> 00:12:36.640
here. I'm going to plot treatment. And I'm similarly weighting the data in the same way

00:12:36.640 --> 00:12:42.880
that I did in the average comparisons call. And you can see that I plotted the groups here on

00:12:42.880 --> 00:12:46.960
the x-axis. And I've got conversion rate on the y, plus confidence intervals. Always good to

00:12:46.960 --> 00:12:53.679
communicate uncertainty. So my colleague was like, whoa, that was so easy. You've saved me so much

00:12:53.679 --> 00:13:00.000
boilerplate. I said, yeah. And it gets even better. Plot predictions returns a ggplot object. So if

00:13:00.000 --> 00:13:04.960
you've got a theme that you really like, or a company theme that you have to follow, you can

00:13:04.960 --> 00:13:11.840
just tack that on to the end of the plot predictions call. And you can treat it like any other ggplot

00:13:11.840 --> 00:13:20.640
object. You can even map other variables to other aesthetics. So for example, if I wanted to plot

00:13:20.640 --> 00:13:27.280
device type as well, I can just pass that to the by argument as the second element in this character

00:13:27.280 --> 00:13:32.799
array. Now I've got both treatment and control, and I've mapped device type to the color aesthetic.

00:13:35.119 --> 00:13:38.400
My colleague was like, that's amazing. But now I want to visualize the lift. I don't just want

00:13:38.400 --> 00:13:43.280
the conversion rates. And I said, you should try the plot comparisons function. And now we're

00:13:43.280 --> 00:13:50.960
plotting the lift for desktop and mobile, similarly to how we computed it using the average comparisons

00:13:50.960 --> 00:13:55.359
function. You can see that this function signature is almost identical to average comparisons.

00:13:57.359 --> 00:14:02.479
So what I wanted my colleague to take away from this is that you can get started making

00:14:02.479 --> 00:14:06.719
plots that you would have otherwise made with less code using marginal effects.

00:14:07.599 --> 00:14:12.080
Marginal effects returns a ggplot2 object. So if you've got a specific theme that you like,

00:14:12.640 --> 00:14:17.520
you can just tack that on in the ways that you typically would do. And the signatures for

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:22.880
average comparisons, or for these plot functions, look very similar to average comparisons. So

00:14:22.880 --> 00:14:25.200
once you master one, you've mastered them all.

00:14:28.239 --> 00:14:36.559
Now, I told you that this was a true-ish story. I think I owe it to you to tell you what was true

00:14:37.359 --> 00:14:44.960
and what was an exaggeration. And the truth is, there was no colleague. I was the colleague.

00:14:44.960 --> 00:14:51.359
This is my story. And this is a DM from that bird website where I'm DMing somebody called Noah,

00:14:51.359 --> 00:14:56.400
and you can see exactly that this is what I asked. I said, I run this experiment. I've got

00:14:56.400 --> 00:15:00.400
some heterogeneity of treatment effect. I fit this model. But my stakeholders want something

00:15:00.400 --> 00:15:06.239
called relative risk. It's simple. It's very comparable to lift. I want to use marginal

00:15:06.239 --> 00:15:13.200
effects. How do I do this? And is this even the right tool? And so I would not be up here without

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:18.880
the help of the authors of marginal effects and everybody in the stats Twitter community.

00:15:18.880 --> 00:15:26.880
So thank you to them. And there is so much that I couldn't fit into a 20-minute talk.

00:15:26.880 --> 00:15:30.960
So my call to action for all of you is to go to marginal effects.com,

00:15:30.960 --> 00:15:34.960
where there are tons of vignettes, docs, and memes, some of which I've wrote.

00:15:36.159 --> 00:15:38.960
And I'm not talking about the vignettes or the docs. I didn't write any of those.

00:15:39.280 --> 00:15:47.440
Seriously, this library is like a godsend to me. I bet that when we all open RStudio,

00:15:47.440 --> 00:15:52.080
we do two things. We load tidyverse and load in data. And honestly, the second thing that I do

00:15:52.080 --> 00:15:56.159
is load in marginal effects. It's that useful to me, and it does way more than I've said here.

00:15:56.159 --> 00:16:01.679
So please go to marginaleffects.com, see what this library can do. And that brings me to the

00:16:01.679 --> 00:16:06.799
end of my talk. Thank you so much for coming and listening to me. And I'll see you next time.

00:16:08.960 --> 00:16:23.440
It means a lot to me, and I'll see you all in 355.23 souls. That's about a year. So thanks so much.

